By fitting the experimentally measured distribution to Eq. (3), the relevant nucleation parameters A*, W*, and σ may be determined. According to the coupled-flux model16, A* is the more appropriate parameter for studying the effects of stirring since it contains a combination of the interfacial attachment kinetics and the diffusion coefficient in the liquid. Initially, melting/solidification cycles were performed in vacuum under the most quiescent condition possible (minimum positioner voltage and heater off) and the parameters A*, W*, and σ were determined by fitting to Eq. (3). Thereafter, to investigate the effect of stirring, σ was kept constant and A* was varied to give the best fit to the nucleation data obtained with increased stirring. In all cases, the driving free energy was estimated using the Turnbull approximation36, ΔG = ΔHfΔT/Tl, where ΔHf is the heat of fusion and \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
